'''Brevetoxin''' (PbTx), or brevetoxins, are a suite of cyclic [[ether#Polyethers|polyether]] compounds produced naturally by a species of [[dinoflagellate]] known as ''[[Karenia brevis]]''.  Brevetoxins are neurotoxins that bind to [[voltage-gated sodium channel]]s in nerve cells, leading to disruption of normal neurological processes and causing the illness clinically described as [[neurotoxic shellfish poisoning]] (NSP).<ref name="watkins">{{ cite journal | author = Watkins SM, Reich A, Fleming LE, Hammond R | title = Neurotoxic Shellfish Poisoning | journal = Marine Drugs | year = 2008 | volume = 6 | issue = 3 | pages = 431–455 | pmc = 2579735 | doi = 10.3390/md20080021 | pmid = 19005578 }}</ref>

Although brevetoxins are most well-studied in ''K. brevis'', they are also found in other species of ''[[Karenia (dinoflagellate)|Karenia]]'' and at least one large [[fish kill]] has been traced to brevetoxins in ''[[Chattonella]]''.<ref name="watkins" />

