Other Brevetoxins:
*Brevetoxin-5 (PbTx-5): like PbTx-3, but [[Acetylation|acetylated]] [[hydroxyl]] group in position 38.
*Brevetoxin-6 (PbTx-6): like PbTx-2, but double bond 27-28 is [[Epoxide|epoxidated]].

Brevetoxin-B was synthesized in 1995 by [[K. C. Nicolaou]] and coworkers in 123 steps with 91% average yield (final yield ~9·10<sup>−6</sup>).<ref>{{cite journal | title = Total Synthesis of Brevetoxin B. 3. Final Strategy and Completion | author = Nicolaou KC, Rutjes FP, Theodorakis EA, Tiebes J, Sato M, Untersteller E | journal = Journal of the American Chemical Society | year = 1995 | volume = 117 | issue = 41 | pages = 10252–10263 | doi = 10.1021/ja00146a010 }}</ref> and in 2004 a total of 90 steps with an average 93% yield for each step (0.14% overall).<ref name=bb>{{ cite journal | title = Total Synthesis of Brevetoxin-B | author = Matsuo G, Kawamura K, Hori N, Matsukura H,  Nakata T | journal = Journal of the American Chemical Society | year = 2004 | volume = 126 | issue = 44 | pages = 14374–14376 | doi = 10.1021/ja0449269 | url = http://www.chem.queensu.ca/courses/09/CHEM223/Handouts/BrevetoxinSynthesis.pdf | format = pdf }}</ref>

[[K. C. Nicolaou]] and coworkers reported their synthesis of Brevetoxin-1 in 1998.<ref>{{ cite journal | author = Nicolaou KC, Yang Z, Shi GQ, Gunzner JL, Agrios KA, Gärtner P | title = Total Synthesis of Brevetoxin A | journal = Nature | year = 1998 | volume = 392 | issue = 6673 | pages = 264–269 | doi = 10.1038/32623 | pmid=9521320}}</ref> In 2009, Michael Crimmins and co-workers reported their synthesis of Brevetoxin-1 as well.<ref>{{ cite journal | author = Crimmins MT, Zuccarello JL, Ellis JM, McDougall PJ, Haile PA, Parrish JD, Emmitte KA | title = Total Synthesis of Brevetoxin A | journal =  Organic Letters | year = 2009 | volume = 11 | issue = 2 | pages = 489–492 | doi = 10.1021/ol802710u }}</ref>

== Biosynthesis ==
A proposed biosynthetic route includes a novel [[polyketide]] formation involving  [[Claisen condensation]] of a dicarboxylic acid with the alpha-position of  the second  carboxylic function with a loss of a carboxyl group.<ref>{{ cite journal | author = Chou HN, Shimizu Y | title = Biosynthesis  of Brevetoxins. Evidence for the Mixed Origin of  the Backbone Carbon Chain and the  Possible Involvement of  Dicarboxylic Acids | journal = Journal of the American Chemical Society | year = 1987 | volume = 109 | issue = 7 | pages = 2184–2185 | doi = 10.1021/ja00241a048 }}</ref>

